T1  - Community Matters: Realistic Group Conflict Theory and the Impact of Diversity
AU  - Brief, Arthur P.
AU  - Umphress, Elizabeth E.
AU  - Dietz, Joerg
AU  - Burrows, John W.
AU  - Butz, Rebecca M.
AU  - Scholten, Lotte
Y1  - 2005/10/01
PY  - 2005
DA  - 2005/10/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amj.2005.18803925
DO  - 10.5465/amj.2005.18803925
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 830
EP  - 844
VL  - 48
IS  - 5
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - We conducted two studies that bring communities into the study of organizational demographics. Reasoning from a realistic group conflict theory base, we predicted (1) negative white reactions to racial and ethnic diversity in organizations and (2) moderation of this relationship by whites' diversity experiences in their communities. Data from the National Organizations Study and an experiment supported our hypotheses. The closer whites lived to blacks (Study 1) and the more interethnic conflict the former perceived in their communities (Study 2), the more negatively they responded to diverse workplaces. Our discussion focuses on understanding organizations as reflections of their environments.
AB  - We conducted two studies that bring communities into the study of organizational demographics. Reasoning from a realistic group conflict theory base, we predicted (1) negative white reactions to racial and ethnic diversity in organizations and (2) moderation of this relationship by whites' diversity experiences in their communities. Data from the National Organizations Study and an experiment supported our hypotheses. The closer whites lived to blacks (Study 1) and the more interethnic conflict the former perceived in their communities (Study 2), the more negatively they responded to diverse workplaces. Our discussion focuses on understanding organizations as reflections of their environments.
